# Next.js 16 Rules

- Target `Next.js 16` semantics first: `App Router`, async `generateMetadata`, `proxy.ts` instead of legacy middleware naming, and production builds that may use `webpack` explicitly when ecosystem compatibility requires it.
- For this repo, do not assume `contentlayer/generated` exists in clean CI. Any build flow, rule, or refactor that touches build config must preserve the explicit Contentlayer prebuild step before `next build`.
- Prefer Server Components by default. Add `"use client"` only for browser APIs, event handlers, local interactive state, or client-only libraries.
- Never access `window`, `document`, `location`, `localStorage`, or `navigator` at module scope. Read them inside effects, callbacks, or client-only branches to avoid hydration drift.
- Use `dynamic(..., { ssr: false })` only for truly browser-only dependencies. When you use it, provide a loading shell with the same approximate footprint to avoid CLS.
- Treat skeletons as optional decoration, not default architecture. Keep them only when async UI would otherwise change layout height.
- Use `next/image` intentionally:
  - local/public images: explicit `width` and `height`, or `fill` plus a sized parent
  - `fill` images must include `sizes`
  - never combine `priority` with `loading="lazy"`
  - use `priority` only for above-the-fold/LCP images
  - prefer plain `img` for arbitrary user/markdown URLs when intrinsic size is unknown
- Shared image wrappers must not rewrite remote URLs, `data:` URLs, or `blob:` URLs. Only normalize local string paths.
- For SEO metadata, always preserve `metadataBase`, canonical alternates, and locale-aware URLs. Do not reintroduce relative Open Graph/Twitter image warnings.
- Mobile-first is required. Start with compact spacing, smaller typography, and stable single-column flows; then enhance for tablet/desktop with `md`/`lg` breakpoints. Avoid desktop-only assumptions in forms, toolbars, and card grids.
- Prefer CSS/Tailwind responsive layout over runtime viewport detection. Reach for JS resize listeners only when CSS cannot solve the problem.
- Keep route handlers and fetches cache-aware. Use explicit cache headers or Next fetch options when data freshness matters.
- After meaningful `app`, `components`, `layouts`, or config changes, run the relevant lint/build verification and sanity-check both mobile-sized and desktop-sized routes when the UI surface changed.
